</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="108" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="108">
<taxonomicName authority="Hilsenhoff" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Acilius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acilius sylvanus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sylvanus">Acilius sylvanus Hilsenhoff</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="108" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="108">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="108">This species is known from Prince Edward Island by a single specimen record from Prince County (Table 2).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="108" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="108">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="108">
These beetles occur in the emergent zone of sun-warmed permanent or semi-permanent ponds in forested area (
<bibRefCitation author="Larson, DJ" journalOrPublisher="NRC Research Press, Ottawa" pageId="15" pageNumber="118" title="Predaceous diving beetles Coleoptera: Dytiscidae) of the Nearctic region, with emphasis on the fauna of Canada and Alaska." year="2000">Larson et al. 2000</bibRefCitation>
). In Prince Edward Island, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Acilius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acilius sylvanus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sylvanus">Acilius sylvanus</taxonomicName>
was collected in a permanent pond on clay bottom located at the edge of a spruce and aspen forest (Tables 1).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="108" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="108">Distribution in the Maritime Ecozone.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="108">
This species is known only from the neighboring Province of New Brunswick (
<bibRefCitation author="Webster, RP" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Acadian Entomological Society" pageId="16" pageNumber="119" pagination="38 - 45" title="New predaceous diving beetle (Coleoptera: Dytiscidae) records for New Brunswick and Canada with new distribution information on some rarely collected species." volume="4" year="2008">Webster 2008</bibRefCitation>
). The presence of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Acilius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acilius sylvanus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sylvanus">Acilius sylvanus</taxonomicName>
in Prince Edward Island represents the easternmost record of this species in Canada.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
